masked_reference_solution:
We have  \[\frac{1}{2} x^6 y^7 = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{M}{N}\right)^6\left(\frac{O}{P}\right)^7 = \frac{1}{2}\cdot \frac{M^6}{N^6} \cdot \frac{O^7}{P^7}
=\frac{1}{2} \cdot\frac{M^6}{M^7} \cdot \frac{O^7}{O^6} = \frac{1}{2}\cdot \frac{1}{N} \cdot O = \boxed{\frac{Q}{R}}.\]
We also could have tackled this problem quickly by noticing that if $x=\frac{M}{N}$ and $y=\frac{O}{P}$, then $x*y=1$, so $\frac{1}{2}x^6y^7 = \frac{1}{2} (x*y)^6y=\frac{1}{2}\cdot 1^6y = \frac{1}{2}y = \frac{O}{P}$.

reference_solution:
We have  \[\frac{1}{2} x^6 y^7 = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{3}{4}\right)^6\left(\frac43\right)^7 = \frac{1}{2}\cdot \frac{3^6}{4^6} \cdot \frac{4^7}{3^7}
=\frac{1}{2} \cdot\frac{3^6}{3^7} \cdot \frac{4^7}{4^6} = \frac{1}{2}\cdot \frac{1}{3} \cdot 4 = \boxed{\frac{2}{3}}.\]
We also could have tackled this problem quickly by noticing that if $x=\frac34$ and $y=\frac43$, then $xy=1$, so $\frac{1}{2}x^6y^7 = \frac{1}{2} (xy)^6y=\frac{1}{2}\cdot 1^6y = \frac{1}{2}y = \frac{2}{3}$.

