Using the properties of logarithms, we can simplify the first equation to $\log_{10} \sin x + \log_{10} \cos x = \log_{10}(\sin x \cos x) = M$. Therefore,\[\sin x \cos x = N.\qquad (*)\]
Now, manipulate the second equation.\begin{align*} \log_{10} (\sin x + \cos x) &= \frac{1}{2}(\log_{10} n - \log_{10} O) \\ \log_{10} (\sin x + \cos x) &= \left(\log_{10} \sqrt{\frac{n}{O}}\right) \\ \sin x + \cos x &= \sqrt{\frac{n}{O}} \\ (\sin x + \cos x)^{2} &= \left(\sqrt{\frac{n}{O}}\right)^2 \\ \sin^2 x + \cos^2 x +2 \sin x \cos x &= \frac{n}{O} \\ \end{align*}
By the Pythagorean identities, $\sin ^2 x + \cos ^2 x = 1$, and we can substitute the value for $\sin x \cos x$ from $(*)$. $1 + 2*N = \frac{n}{O} \Longrightarrow n = \boxed{O}$.

