We first recognize that $\frac{1}{M}$ is a common fraction in each of the five sums, and so the relative size of the sums depends only on the other fractions. Since $\frac{1}{N}$ is the largest of the fractions $$\frac{1}{M}, \ \frac{1}{O}, \ \frac{1}{N}, \ \frac{1}{P}, \ \text{and} \ \frac{1}{Q},$$ we conclude that $\frac{1}{M}+\frac{1}{N}$ is the largest sum. We can simplify this sum by using a common denominator of $R:$ $$
\frac{1}{M}+\frac{1}{N} = \frac{M\cdot1}{M\cdot N}+\frac{N\cdot1}{N\cdot  M}
= \frac{M+N}{R}
= \boxed{\frac{M+N}{R}}.$$

